[Patient] How much fluid should I drink in a day to manage my heart failure?
[Educator] Aim for around 1.5 to 2 liters of fluid per day, including water and other drinks.
[Patient] Can I drink coffee or tea?
[Educator] Limit caffeine intake as it can affect your heart. Opt for decaffeinated options.
[Patient] What about alcohol?
[Educator] It's best to avoid alcohol as it can worsen heart failure symptoms.
[Patient] How do I know if I'm retaining too much fluid?
[Educator] Watch for swelling in your legs, sudden weight gain, or difficulty breathing.
[Patient] Is it okay to have salty foods?
[Educator] Limit salt intake to avoid fluid retention. Choose low-sodium options when possible.
[Patient] What about fruits and vegetables with high water content?
[Educator] Enjoy fruits like watermelon or cucumbers in moderation. They can contribute to your fluid intake.
[Patient] How can I track my fluid intake?
[Educator] Use a measuring cup to keep track of how much you're drinking throughout the day.
[Patient] Can I have soups or broths?
[Educator] Opt for low-sodium soups or broths to manage your fluid intake effectively.
[Patient] Thank you for the advice. I'll make sure to follow these recommendations.
[Educator] You're welcome. Remember, managing your fluid intake is key to controlling your heart failure.